Johnson Okafor Equities advanced on signs that China may be planning further measures to support its economy as it reels from a virus-induced slowdown and after US data pointed to solid growth. According to Bloomberg News, gains for chipmakers and tech hardware companies led the S&P 500 Index toward a fresh record high after Bloomberg News reported that China’s latest moves to aid growth include possible bailouts for hard-hit industries. The dollar climbed to a four-month high after data on housing starts and building permits exceeded analysts’ estimates. Treasuries held steady. The Stoxx Europe 600 Index reached new highs, and shares climbed in Tokyo, Hong Kong and Sydney. The yen fell to a nine-month low on concern Japan’s economy may slip into a recession. Oil rose as US sanctions on Russia’s largest producer and conflict in Libya put the focus on supply threats. Global stocks with China exposure have yet to see sustained relative recovery. Copyright PUNCH.
